shared_text:
Lafourche Parish President Archie Chaisson
Yesterday at 2:09 AM ¬∑

Quick Construction Update:

The contractor tasked with putting up the new signals on Hwy 3235 is set to be onsite Monday. This means the final asphalt work will begin again soon and we can get that road back open.

Work will also begin this month on the approaches and deck of the McCloud Bridge on LA 308 in Lockport. That work will smooth the rough and broken surfaces in the bridge. It it anticipated, weather depending, that the work will be completed by the end of the month.

#LafourcheProgress

Do you live in a flood-prone structure and need assistance with elevating, reconstructing, or selling your home?

#TuesdayTip:
Lafourche Parish Government is working with FEMA on a competitive grant program to provide funds to mitigate flood-prone structures. While there is no guarantee that you will be selected, all property owners with a current contract for flood insurance and at least two separate NFIP claim payments may apply. For assistance or inquiries, please contact Lionel Lagarde, Jr. (Grant Manager) at 985.493.6673.
More Information: https://www.fema.gov/grants/mitigation/floods

post_text: Residential Garbage service will be suspended for Monday, August 24, 2020, due to the landfill's closure. Riverbirch Renewable Energy will have boom trucks picking up bulky waste throughout the parish until such time that weather conditions deteriorate. Please remove any roadside garbage cans to prevent them from being blown into the drainage system during high wind periods.

A decision about residential garbage service on Tuesday will be made during the day Monday. Please remove any roadside garbage cans to prevent them from being blown into the drainage system during high wind periods.

post_text:
As Tropical Storm Marco and Laura approach coastal landfall, Parish President Archie Chaisson has issued a Mandatory Evacuation for all residents and businesses South of the Leon Theriot Flood Gate and other low-lying areas. The Mandatory Evacuation takes effect Sunday, August 23rd, 2020 at 12:00 PM. In order to accommodate evacuees that will need shelter, the Recreation Center (241 Recreation Drive, Raceland, LA 70394) will open August 23rd, 2020 at 12:00 PM.

Please contact the Lafourche Parish Emergency Operations Center at 985-537-7603 prior to evacuating to the shelter so that we can assist you with instructions. Emergency Operations personnel will continue to monitor storm developments and remain available 24-7 through the duration of these storms. Updates will be shared as new information becomes available.

On this #ThankfulThursday, we celebrate Ashton Dillon, who was presented with the Lafourche Parish Outstanding Citizen Award.
Ashton has been coaching youth sports for 18 years as a volunteer and is responsible for many young athletic scholarships for male and female athletes. He has had many personal obstacles to overcome which has led to his unique ability to reach out to young people who view him as an inspiration. Our Parish is fortunate to have such an amazing citizen among us. Congratulations Ashton Dillon!

Here is the latest update on Tropical Depression #8 in the central Gulf of Mexico: Landfall is expected along the Texas coastline this weekend.

Changes Since The Last Update...
‚Ä¢ Forecast rainfall totals have increased slightly across all of southeastern Louisiana and southern Mississippi (see graphic below).
‚Ä¢ Portions of southeastern Louisiana and southern Mississippi has been upgraded to a SLIGHT RISK for excessive rainfall Thursday and Friday. MARGINAL RISK now extends into Saturday.
shared_text:
US National Weather Service New Orleans Louisiana
July 23 at 12:47 PM ¬∑

It's 7:00AM: Here's the latest on Tropical Depression 8 in the central Gulf of Mexico. This system will continue drifting west-northwest and steadily strengthen into a tropical storm through late-week and into the weekend.

‚òîÔ∏è Impacts associated with Tropical Depression 8 include the risk for locally heavy rainfall today and tomorrow. Portions of the area remain in a Marginal Risk of excessive rainfall, with now areas south of I-10/12 in SE LA now upgraded to a Slight Risk. Watch for flash flooding in these outlooked areas!

üåä No changes to the Coastal Flood Advisory in effect. Higher than normal tides may produce some coastal flooding along coastal SE LA / S MS and the tidal lake coastlines. More so in/around areas that traditionally see coastal flooding from enhanced onshore wind flow.

Stay tuned for more updates!

Tropical Update as of 2 p.m. 7/22/20

Changes Since Last Update:
‚Ä¢ The disturbance now has a 80% chance (high) of development in the next 5 days / 70% chance (high) in the next 48 hours. Tropical depression is likely to develop during the next day or two as the system moves west-northwest at about 10 mph.
‚Ä¢ Tropical storm watches or warnings could be required for portions of south Louisiana later today or tonight.
‚Ä¢ Local impacts are largely the same as before, but could be trending higher for heavy rainfall, coastal flooding and wind over the next couple of days.

Help us wish Mrs. Cora Lee Smith a very HAPPY 104th BIRTHDAY!

At last night's Council Meeting, Lafourche Parish President Archie Chaisson honored Mrs. Cora Lee Smith with "A Certificate of Recognition" in celebration of her 104th birthday.

Mrs. Smith was born in the St. Charles Community, was the wife of Kermit Smith, is the mother of four children, and taught 4th grade for 25 years at St. Charles Elementary (*and never missed a day of school*). She now spends her time enjoying visits from family and friends.

NWS Overview: Heat and Weather Advisory

WHAT:
Today: HEAT ADVISORY IN EFFECT for heat index values in the danger level.
Tomorrow (Thursday) into Friday: Marginal Risk of excessive rainfall and flooding

WHEN:
Heat Advisory in effect today; Excessive rainfall and flooding threat is late Thursday and Friday, possibly extending into the weekend

WHERE:
For the Heat Advisory: all of southeast and east central Louisiana and extreme south Mississippi.
For the Excessive Rainfall threat: mainly north of Lake Pontchartrain/Florida Parishes into south Mississippi late Thursday and Thursday night, and across the entire area on Friday and Friday night.

Impacts:
The main threats associated with long exposure in heat will be:
‚Ä¢ Muscle Cramps
‚Ä¢ Heat exhaustion
‚Ä¢ Possibly heatstroke

Heat indices of 103 to 109 are expected during the late morning and especially this afternoon. The local heat advisory criteria is index values equal to or greater than 108.

Activity of the day: Erupting Volcano

Items:
Styrofoam cup
Crayola Soft Dough
Baking Soda
Vinegar

We used a styrofoam cup upside down with a hole cut out the top for our base- then we wrapped it with dough to resemble a volcano.

Eruption steps:
2 table spoons of baking soda
2-3 squirts of dye color of choice
1/2 cup of vinegar üåã

This is a fun and easy activity to do at home.

Public comment will be allowed by completing a Public Wishing to Address the Council form found on the Lafourche Parish Government website (www.lafourchegov.org) and returning it to the Council Clerk via email at (babincb@lafourchegov.org) or by fax at (985)-449-4012 no later than 30 minutes prior to the start of the meeting. Forms received by the deadline will be read by the Chairman during the Public Wishing to Address the Council portion of the meeting.

LAFOURCHEGOV.ORG
Lafourche Parish Council Meeting

Reminder: Mandatory Evacuation South of Golden Meadow

Parish President Archie Chaisson issued a Mandatory Evacuation for all residents and businesses South of the Leon Theriot Flood Gate (Golden Meadow) and other low-lying areas.

The Mandatory Evacuation takes effect this evening, June 6th, 2020 at 6 p.m. In order to accommodate evacuees that will need shelter, the Recreation Center (241 Recreation Drive, Raceland, LA 70394) opened June 6th, 2020 at 2 p.m.

Please contact the Lafourche Parish Emergency Operations Center at 985-537-7603 prior to evacuating to the shelter so that we can assist you with instructions.

post_text: Update from Port Fourchon: LA 1 Road Status
shared_text:
Port Fourchon
June 6 at 8:26 PM ¬∑

üëáüëáüëá
NOTICE: WATER ENCROACHING ON LOW-LYING AREAS ON LA 1 BELOW GOLDEN MEADOW LOCK

As Tropical Storm Cristobal approaches, Port Fourchon Harbor Police report that rising water levels (as of 3:15 pm today, June 6th) are encroaching on low-lying areas of LA 1 and Old LA 1. Drivers should be especially cautious when traveling roadways soon to be overtopped in some areas. Water is approaching the fog line on the northbound shoulder just outside of Leeville, at Tidewater Dock in Golden Meadow, and in front of The Seafood Shed in Golden Meadow. The area of Old LA 1 from BBY Marina to RSI Shipyard has water approaching or across the northbound lane, and the area of RSI Shipyard is completely covered. Please also note the road remains OPEN at this time, but we anticipate water levels to be high enough to close it at some point later tonight.

As Tropical Storm Cristobal approaches coastal landfall, Parish President Archie Chaisson has issued a Mandatory Evacuation for all residents and businesses South of the Leon Theriot Flood Gate and other low-lying areas.

The Mandatory Evacuation takes effect Saturday, June 6th, 2020 at 6 p.m. In order to accommodate evacuees that will need shelter, the Recreation Center (241 Recreation Drive, Raceland, LA 70394) will open June 6th, 2020 at 2 p.m.

Please contact the Lafourche Parish Emergency Operations Center at 985-537-7603 prior to evacuating to the shelter so that we can assist you with instructions. Emergency Operations personnel will continue to monitor storm developments and remain available 24-7 through the duration of the storm. Updates will be shared as new information becomes available.

President Archie Chaisson has declared a State of Emergency for Lafourche Parish in anticipation of heavy rain, forecasted storm surge, and possible flooding due to Tropical Storm Cristobal. The National Weather Service issued a Flash Flood Watch in effect through next Tuesday, June 9th, 2020. Rain totals exceeding 10 inches are possible.

Public works crews are working to ensure pumps throughout Lafourche Parish remain fully operational and continue to clean canals and catch basins ahead of the storm. Residents are also encouraged to clean near their homes and report requests for assistance or any flooding to the EOC (Emergency Operations Center) at 985-532-8174.

post_text: Parish President Archie Chaisson, DPW Director Dillon Baronne, and Parish Administrator Mitch Orgeron held a meeting this morning going over parish preparation for Tropical Storm Cristobal. They also held a readiness meeting with all DPW supervisors to take input on what has and hasn't worked over the years to strengthen their plan. President Chaisson said, "We have been preparing for this knowing we were getting closer to hurricane season. Now, it's time we put those plans into motion to keep our residents safe."

post_text:
#ThursdayTip - Hurricane Preparedness

With hurricane season off to an active start, the Department of Children and Family Services (DCFS) is encouraging all Louisiana households who are not currently receiving Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) benefits to make registering for Disaster SNAP (DSNAP) a part of their hurricane preparedness game plan ‚Äì even if they have registered before.

DSNAP provides eligible low- to moderate-income households who do not normally receive SNAP benefits with help buying groceries due to lost income or damages following a disaster.

Register: http://www.dcfs.louisiana.gov/page/360

post_text: NWS- Here is the latest information on Tropical Storm Cristobal. The storm is currently over the Yucatan Peninsula where it is slowly weakening. Cristobal may weaken to a Tropical Depression in the next few hours. The storm is expected to move back over the Gulf on Friday and move northward toward the northern Gulf Coast over the weekend where some re-strengthening is possible. The main concerns for our area will be heavy rainfall and the potential for coastal flooding. A Flood Watch is in effect for much of the area through Tuesday morning.

Lafourche Parish President Archie Chaisson, the Emergency Operations Center, and the Public Works Department will continue to monitor the Tropical Storm Cristobal developments.

The risk of heavy rain and wind is expected in our area this weekend. In order to prepare, sandbag locations are open throughout Lafourche Parish beginning tomorrow, June 4th, 2020 at 6:30 a.m.

Sand and sandbags will be available for residents at self-serve locations. Please bring a shovel, be prepared to fill bags, and only take what is needed.

You can access the latest information and updates at www.lafourchegov.org or follow us on Facebook @lafourchegov.

Lafourche Parish President Archie Chaisson
June 3 at 12:42 AM ¬∑

Hurricane season is now upon us. Now is the time to get prepared and get those essential items ready and in one spot. Now is also the time to think of what ‚Äúnew normal‚Äù items we need to pack in our hurricane stash. Packing things like wipes, hand sanitizer and a mask are some of the things we should include now.

With the anticipated impacts from T. S. Cristobal please do not place any more bulk items at the road for pick up like tree limbs. We are working hard to catch up and adding more items now may cause them to be missed and they could end up in culverts or clogg ditches.

Stay weather aware and stay tuned to the Lafourche Parish Government website and social media pages for the latest.

#LafourcheStrong #WeatherAware #GetAGamePlan

post_text: NHC- Hurricane Hunters find that Tropical Depression 3 has become Tropical Storm Cristobal. More info: hurricanes.gov
shared_text:
NOAA NWS National Hurricane Center
June 2 at 4:31 PM ¬∑

...DEPRESSION STRENGTHENS TO A TROPICAL STORM...

Observations from an Air Force Reserve Unit Hurricane Hunter aircraft indicate that Tropical Depression Three has strengthened into Tropical Storm Cristobal (pronounced krees-TOH-bahl). The maximum winds are estimated to be 40 mph (65 km/h) with higher gusts.

It's centered as of 11:15 a.m. CDT about 150 miles (245 km) west-southwest of Campeche, Mexico, moving toward the west-southwest at 3 mph (km/h).

The next complete advisory will be issued by NHC at 4 p.m. CDT with an intermediate advisory at 1 p.m. CDT www.hurricanes.gov

Observations from an Air Force Reserve Unit Hurricane Hunter aircraft indicate that Tropical Depression Three has strengthened into Tropical Storm Cristobal (pronounced krees-TOH-bahl). The maximum winds are estimated to be 40 mph (65 km/h) with higher gusts.

It's centered as of 11:15 a.m. CDT about 150 miles (245 km) west-southwest of Campeche, Mexico, moving toward the west-southwest at 3 mph (km/h).

The next complete advisory will be issued by NHC at 4 p.m. CDT with an intermediate advisory at 1 p.m. CDT www.hurricanes.gov

COVID-19 Testing Site to Close in Raceland:

This Friday, May 29th, 2020 the Raceland COVID-19 drive-thru testing site will close at noon for the foreseeable future.

"We cannot thank the State and National Guard enough for their help in getting the site up and running and for their hard work with daily operations. Providing our residents with the ability to be tested at their convenience was a great way to truly see how our community was doing and offered peace of mind," said President Chaisson.

Lafourche officials will continue to work with LDH (Louisiana Department of Heath) and GOHSEP (Governor's Office of Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness) to bring the mobile testing lab to Lafourche Parish, should the need arise.

Today, May, 21st, 2020, President Chaisson activated a debris removal contract with DRC Emergency Services to bring in additional resources for the collection of bulky waste debris throughout Lafourche Parish.

Due to COVID-19 stay-at-home orders in combination with recent severe weather events, the volume of residential solid waste has increased substantially. River Birch Renewable Energy, our solid waste service provider, and DRC Emergency Services will partner to collect and remove debris as quickly as possible.

Please continue to place as much solid waste and debris into the parish issued cans as possible. Note that these additional services are provided for residential customers only, no contractor debris. #LafourcheStrong

shared_text:
CDC
May 19 at 3:30 PM ¬∑

If you operate a pool or water playground, you can help prevent the spread of COVID-19. Follow these health and safety tips:

‚Ä¢ Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces at least daily
‚Ä¢ Minimize the use of shared equipment
‚Ä¢ Educate staff and guests about when to stay home
‚Ä¢ Post healthy hygiene tips
‚Ä¢ Encourage social distancing of at least 6 feet
‚Ä¢ Encourage frequent handwashing and covering coughs and sneezes
‚Ä¢ Ensure guests do not wear face coverings in the water

See more CDC considerations: https://bit.ly/2Wn9I44.

Highs today will be in the mid to upper 80s, but it's likely to be several degrees cooler on Wednesday with more clouds. Overnight lows tonight will be in the mid and upper 60s for most areas.

We officially enter Phase 1 of reopening on Friday, May 15th, 2020.

Restaurants, coffee shops, and cafes will be able to be open to the public for indoor table service at 25% of their State Fire Marshal capacity, with continued allowance for additional outdoor seating with social distancing.

Businesses that the Governor will still require to be closed include: tattoo parlors, massage and spas, bars (unless they have a LDH food license) and children amusement.

Lafourche Parish Announces the Cancellation of Summer Recreation Programs:

Lafourche Parish President Archie Chaisson announced that due to COVID-19 and the phased reopening of the Parish, State, and Nation, all Lafourche Parish sponsored summer recreation programs are cancelled.

‚ÄúThe safety of our children and staff is paramount, and by not knowing what phase we will be in by June 1st, we are making the precautionary decision to cancel summer recreation programs,‚Äù said President Chaisson.

In conjunction with this decision, individual Recreation Districts will make their own decisions about allowing league play on their fields, while following CDC and State Fire Marshal social distancing guidelines.
